  "prompt": "Why isn't WhatsApp fixing the \"copy multiple messages includes date and time stamp along with it\" bug?",
  "response": "The inclusion of date and time stamps when copying multiple messages on WhatsApp is not necessarily a \"bug\" but rather a design choice by the developers. Here are a few reasons why WhatsApp might not have \"fixed\" this issue:\n\n1. **Intentional Design**: WhatsApp may consider the date and time stamps as important context for the conversation. Including them ensures that the copied messages retain their chronological context when shared or pasted elsewhere.\n\n2. **User Expectations**: Many users might expect or appreciate having the timestamps included, as it helps preserve the integrity and order of the conversation when they copy and share messages.\n\n3. **Technical Limitations**: Changing the way messages are copied might require significant changes to the app's backend or user interface, which could introduce new bugs or complexities.\n\n4. **Prioritization**: WhatsApp\u2019s development team might prioritize other features or fixes that they consider more critical or impactful for the majority of users.\n\n5. **Lack of Widespread Complaints**: If the issue hasn\u2019t been widely reported or isn\u2019t causing major inconvenience for most users, it might not be high on the list of fixes.\n\nIf this feature bothers you, you can provide feedback directly to WhatsApp through the app\u2019s settings (Settings > Help > Contact Us). This might help them understand user preferences and consider changes in future updates. Alternatively, you could manually remove the timestamps after copying the messages.",
